reviews: [{'author_name': 'rebecca ballantyne', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108903604925621401045/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-EkkXBANKc9U/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/AMZuucm9POohKtzoWmK19JyuHaB3NnGWRA/s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3/photo.jpg', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 years ago', 'text': 'I just attended for the first time today.  It was for a funeral service unfortunately, but I thought it was one of the most unique churches I have ever been in.  The architecture of the sanctuary is stunning. I would recommend this place for healing.", 'time': 1589834515}, {'author_name': 'Dan Oke', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/103304100530008901272/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GghmRRuFAxBJyWBaGRd6ZrTSZhZOMJfOZIuo4o_=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a year ago', 'text': 'A safe place where everyone of all ages/races/genders/orientations are welcome. The parishioners are kind and welcoming and the rectors are open-minded, progressive and educated in a variety of topics outside of scripture. This helps to make the service and sermons relate to everyone on a very practical, kind and human level.

The children/youth program focuses on using the Bible as a guideline to help build a strong moral compass. The students are encouraged to explore their faith by asking questions, playing games, keeping a gratitude journal and so much more.

In 1925 it became Cook\'s United Church. In 1891 they held the first Garden Party, attended by hundreds for miles around. reviews: [{'author_name': 'hamed izadi', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/103785752395194275920/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gi8tueIvConkx1_JWHOO_WNqKMZU55fVQv-_AhO=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 years ago', 'text': 'Great pastor with amazing sermons, warm church family, very welcome people', 'time': 1537635068}, {'author_name': 'Church Goer', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/112563255178208007917/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-UVyBqRXu_uU/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/AMZuucmnwyO_B8YXiZ_0MLqAU4-aw47VNQ/s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo/photo.jpg', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '6 years ago', 'text': 'A cute little church in a quiet street in Unionville filled with genuine and devoted pursuers of Christ…  I went to Unionville Baptist Church on the last Sunday of the year.  It was a diverse congregation in terms of age and ethnicity.  I really liked their simple acoustic worship that mixed contemporary notes with hymns.  The two joyful vocalists on the stage enhanced the worship atmosphere.  For the coming year, Rev. Chris Meyers encouraged the congregation not to easily settle with spiritual complacency but to zealously pursue Christ and for His commands – to love, to serve, to offer, and to search for any hidden sin.  As the congregation sang the reflective song after the sermon, I saw the elderly lady in front of me singing the “As the Deer - As the deer panteth for the water, so my soul longeth after thee…” with tears.  When the worship service finished, to my surprise, Rev. Meyers ran out to the door to greet me.  Other people also tried to talk to me and to invite me back for the next Sunday. reviews: [{'author_name': 'Queen Christine Ann Stewart-Peterhoff', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/113440252293731344424/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gili5lK8chntYCClgYqgDywIkhs-edW2lizSgs7ag=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '7 months ago', 'text': 'Every summer my Grandparents would take my sisters and I for holidays on Beausoleil Island in Georgian Bay. The Martyr Shrine was a large white church on a hill that we would pass on the way to Beausoleil Island. We would always want to visit the church so one day our mother decided to take us. We were very young so it was really difficult to climb the many stairs up to the Grand Entrance of this very beautiful Shrine. When I entered I was really surprised at what I found inside. It was nothing like I had imagined. It was a definite learning experience into the history of Canada, Religion, Medicine, Politics and even the Sacrifices of this Great Nation. It was definitely an interesting and unforgettable learning experience that I have always cherished. I have been back a couple of times in my life, my favourite was when I brought my daughter for the first time. She loved it too and enjoyed the visit. There have been many additions to the Shrine since I first visited, but there are still so many adventures to see and learn here. The existing church building is actually its fourth building in its neighbourhood.  The stained glass windows in the front and by the two sides of the sanctuary have added much decorative effect to the building.  The website also writes about what to expect in the first visit to the church as newcomers and shows much transparency about how the church is run.\nThe church is resourceful enough to have two services: a contemporary service and a traditional service targeted for difference audiences.  I came visiting the traditional service which composed of hymns, prayers, scriptures reading, choir singing and sermons.  It was a Mother’s day Sunday.  The youth pastor shared a mother’s day message with the children and then had the children distributed beautiful carnation to all ladies in the congregation.  Rev. Peter Ma was also a theological sounded speaker.  He preached about a practical topic about pain and forgiveness in life.  He was very courteous. We reached at around 12 noon. We prayed  the rosary at the reception room After lunch we started the way of the cross at around 1.20. We finished by around  2.30 pm. Near the 10th station there is a huge blue cross - we were told that miracles happen around this area.

We moved near the cross and began the divine mercy  just a little before 3 pm I looked up and saw it was very cloudy all around and it was cold. Exactly at 3 pm I noticed the Sun started to appear very bright just in front of us behind the trees . Suddenly we could  see the clouds changing colours . It was bright blue first and then it changed to a beautiful magenta and then a beautiful gold colour - all 6 of us could see this and became very excited since we knew Mother Mary was present . We all saw the sun turn . The sun appeared like an eclipse and it was in magnificent blue. All of us saw it directly and  were just overcome by the beauty of it. The sun had black lines and was not fully round. It appeared to move around. One lady in the group Miriam saw Jesus appear for a few seconds. Another lady felt peace around her. This happened for around 10 minutes. .The background colours were so magnificent it was truly a momentous moment for all of us . We just kept praising the name of Jesus. We were all crying with joy having witnessed such an incredible event in our lives.
At that moment 2 women and a man walked nearby- we called out to them to look but they could not see anything.

At the end there was a shower- Miriam said this is Gods blessing to all 6 of us. The showers ended soon after. What an amazing day that we will all cherish for the rest of our lives.', 'time': 1539480704}]
